OXFORD.
The annual meeting of the Centre School District will be held on Saturday morning of this week.

J. T. Leek spent a few days here this week, at the home of his mother.

Tuttles' exhibition was advertised at the Chestnut Tree Hill school house last Wednesday evening.]

Miss Emma B. Smith of Owls' Inn, West Haven is visiting with Miss Lois Lurn on Riggs street.

Chas. B. Perry has secured a position ss teacher in the Strait University, New Orleans, La., commencing October 1st.
C B. Perry and W. S. Barnes have been trying the navigating capacity of their canoes, and the more their experience the less the canoes are on top.

The Congregational church and society have accepted Rev. Mr. Snow's resignation to take effect on the 29th, but he will supply during the month of August.

Another hearing was given at the probate office Tuesday in the Bidwell will case, the first having been held on the 14th and adjourned. The contested will was made by Mr. Bidwell four days before his death, giving all his property, variously valued at $5,000 to 10,000, to his wife, thereby setting aside a previous will giving half the property to his wife and half to his grandchildren, the children of Dr. Henry Nettleton of Birmingham. Judge Gillette of Waterbury presided at the hearing by request of Judge Barnes. Attorney Williams is counsel for Mrs. Bidwell, and Wooster, Torrence & Gager for Dr. Nettleton.

